default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultNeuroPAS Global (UK)default Ldefaultimidefaulttdefaultedefaultddefault&#xa0;defaultGary CavazzidefaultCFO/COOdefault&#xa0;defaultDr Steve McVittie MFOMdefaultConsultant Occupational Physician defaultChief Medical Officerdefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultConsultation questions:default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 1: Do you agree that, in future, medical reports for whiplash injury claims should be supplied by independent medical panels, using a standard report form, and should be available equally to claimants, insurers, and (for contested claims) the courts?defaultYes
default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 2; If not, how would you address the problems listed at paras. 35–39 above?defaultN/A
default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 3: Which model should be used for the independent medical panels – defaultAccreditation, national call-off contract or some other variant?defaultAccreditation of Independent medical practitioners (only if a scientifically sound objective medical tool is used to augment the diagnostic process, rather than only using subjective opinion). 
default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 4: Do you consider that an element of peer review should be built into every assessment, or only for a sample of assessments for audit purposes?defaultPeer reviews should be used for a sample of assessments, but only if an augmented diagnostic process is used. If not, a second opinion would be needed for 100% of claims.
default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 6: Should the Small Claims track threshold be increased to £5,000 for RTA related whiplash claims, be increased to £5,000 for all RTA PI claims or not changed?defaultThe threshold should be raised to £5,000 for all RTA related to whiplash claims, but with a caveat that random medical checks being made. 
default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 7: Will there be an impact on the RTA Protocol and could this be mitigated?defaultUnknown
default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 8: What more should the Government consider doing to reduce the cost of exaggerated and/or fraudulent whiplash claims?defaultUse a scientifically sound objective medical tool is to augment the diagnostic process, and stop relying solely on subjective clinical opinion).
defaultQuestion 9: Do you agree with the accompanying equality screening? If not, please explain why.defaultYes
defaultQuestion 10: Can you identify ways in which the procedure under current arrangements impacts on people with protected characteristics? If so please provide evidence of impact.defaultNo, except that reactions to a whiplash experience can be influenced by gender, cultural or social factors. 
defaultQuestion 11: Do you consider that the introduction of independent medical panels to assess whiplash injuries will impact on people with protected characteristics? If so, please give details.defaultNot if suitable code of practice is encompassed with the accreditation process.
default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 12: Do you consider that an increase in the small claims limit for Whiplash/RTA personal injury claims from £1,000 to £5,000 will affect people with protected equality characteristics? If so, please give details.defaultNot if suitable code of practice is encompassed with the accreditation process.
